	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Better times for East African coffee producers </h1>

			
			<h4>
												18 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the International Coffee Organization (ICO), progress in the development of coffee production in Ethiopia has taken projected production for 2011/12 to 9.8 million bags, making Ethiopia ‘the world’s third largest producer after Brazil and Vietnam’. Ethiopian production has doubled in three seasons, stimulated by high prices, which has encouraged investment in the sector. Coffee now accounts for 40% of Ethiopian exports. Ethiopia grows mainly arabica coffee.</p><p><b>Green coffee production (2007–2011 60-kg bags)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="155" valign="top">  &nbsp;
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  <b>Ethiopia</b>
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  <b>Rwanda</b>
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  <b>Tanzania</b>
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="155" valign="top">  2007
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  4,036,000
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  400,000
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  515,000
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="155" valign="top">  2008
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  3,906,000
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  230,000
  </td><td width="155" valign="top">  525,000
  </td>
</tr>

